WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.849 --> 00:00:13.640
[Music] Good day. I'm Norman Wildberger.&nbsp;
Today we want to have a look at the role&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.640 --> 00:00:19.560
of the term "nothing," the concept of nothing,&nbsp;
in mathematics, which historically has been very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:19.560 --> 00:00:25.320
interesting. It's a kind of nebulous concept, of&nbsp;
course, that a lot of people have had different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:25.320 --> 00:00:33.360
points of view towards, and what I'd like&nbsp;
to do is introduce a really dramatically new&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:40.080
way—an additional new way—of thinking about&nbsp;
nothing and its role in mathematics. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:44.960
in preparation for a discussion of that,&nbsp;
let's have a look at some of the history.

00:00:44.960 --> 00:00:52.600
A good place to go back to is the ancient&nbsp;
Babylonians. Babylonians were sort of the geniuses&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.600 --> 00:00:59.920
of the ancient world long before the Greeks came&nbsp;
on the scene. They had a very highly developed,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:06.880
original, and powerful mathematics.&nbsp;
So around 3,000 BC, their culture&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:06.880 --> 00:01:13.560
developed in the Mesopotamian area, between&nbsp;
the Tigris and Euphrates rivers, and they had&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:13.560 --> 00:01:20.080
a sexagesimal system, which means base 60—very&nbsp;
interesting—and they also used a floating-point&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:25.640
positional system very much like the one we&nbsp;
do. So they used basically only two symbols:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:25.640 --> 00:01:30.920
there was a symbol for one and a symbol for ten,&nbsp;
which they wrote with this sort of wedge-like&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.920 --> 00:01:39.800
implement that they used to write on clay tablets.&nbsp;
To express 47, they would make four of these tens&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:39.800 --> 00:01:43.720
and seven of these ones, and they would arrange&nbsp;
them in something like this, and that would be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:43.720 --> 00:01:52.760
47. So they used these to represent the numbers&nbsp;
from 1 to 59—they are the corresponding digits&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:52.760 --> 00:01:59.840
for the Babylonians, just as the numbers 1 to 9&nbsp;
are for us. Well, actually, we use zero as well.

00:02:01.880 --> 00:02:07.080
So then, otherwise, what they did is they had a&nbsp;
base 60 representation so that they would clump&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.080 --> 00:02:15.680
their numbers in various places linearly. So this&nbsp;
representation here—there'd be a 47 visible there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:15.680 --> 00:02:20.400
and here you can see a 21, and here there's&nbsp;
some kind of space, and over here there's a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:20.400 --> 00:02:29.840
2. So this would represent, for them, well, 47,&nbsp;
21 times 60, so this would be the 60s column&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:40.560
and 0 60 squares and 2 60 cubes. So altogether,&nbsp;
2 times 60 cubed plus 21 times 60 (we'll ignore&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:40.560 --> 00:02:48.040
this one) plus 47 for a total of&nbsp;
what we would call 27,037. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:52.280
an interesting aspect of their arithmetic&nbsp;
was that they didn't really have a very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:52.280 --> 00:02:58.360
clear or concrete representation of the decimal&nbsp;
point, so there was some kind of ambiguity in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.360 --> 00:03:06.200
their system. On another occasion, they could&nbsp;
have represented this as being 21 ones, 0 60s,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:06.200 --> 00:03:15.960
2 60 squares, and 47 over 60. This gave them&nbsp;
a flexibility that was actually quite useful.

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:24.440
So what's interesting for us is their use of the&nbsp;
space to represent zeros. They had this very clear&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:24.440 --> 00:03:28.480
idea—they were going to work with powers of&nbsp;
60, and if they were missing a power of 60,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:28.480 --> 00:03:35.640
they'd just leave a space. They weren't going to&nbsp;
put anything there. The reader should be able to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.640 --> 00:03:41.920
see that there's a space in here and sort of&nbsp;
register that they're missing the 60 squares,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.920 --> 00:03:48.960
but they have 60s and 60 cubes. So this is&nbsp;
going back quite a long time, and so this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:56.280
really is a use of the decimal kind of system,&nbsp;
very much like the Hindu-Arabic one that we use,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.280 --> 00:04:00.040
with the notable exception that they're&nbsp;
working in base 60 and that they don't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.040 --> 00:04:08.560
have an explicit form for a placeholder, but&nbsp;
they're using the space pretty much exactly in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:14.680
the corresponding way. So they can certainly deal&nbsp;
with numbers pretty much the same way that we can.

00:04:14.680 --> 00:04:19.560
Now, the Babylonian culture lasted a long&nbsp;
time—we're talking about a several thousand-year&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:19.560 --> 00:04:27.840
span—and in the later part of this time frame,&nbsp;
around 300 BC, there was a great flowering of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:27.840 --> 00:04:36.240
astronomy and work in that direction. And part&nbsp;
of that story was a very interesting development:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:43.240
the Babylonians started to use an explicit&nbsp;
symbol to represent this placeholder that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:43.240 --> 00:04:50.680
previously they just had a space for. So this&nbsp;
is actually the first really recorded use of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.680 --> 00:04:58.440
a symbol for zero, which predates the Hindu&nbsp;
development, actually. So here's what they did:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:04.520
they employed basically a similar kind of&nbsp;
symbol to their number two—just these two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:04.520 --> 00:05:09.480
sort of wedges coming down—but they're now&nbsp;
at an angle and they're kind of a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:09.480 --> 00:05:15.720
above the regular reading of things. So they&nbsp;
could see that as we're reading this here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.720 --> 00:05:23.240
this symbol here represents not an explicit number&nbsp;
two but rather a placeholder for the zero. So they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:23.240 --> 00:05:36.200
could read this as 2 times 60 squared plus 0&nbsp;
times 60 plus 24, which would be our 7,224.

00:05:36.200 --> 00:05:43.400
Now, this symbol here really is only being used as&nbsp;
a placeholder, okay? It's to make more explicit,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:43.400 --> 00:05:52.120
more unambiguous, the fact that there is nothing&nbsp;
in this place, particularly right here. It's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.120 --> 00:05:59.440
not the case that this symbol was used as a&nbsp;
separate number—that was the development that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:59.440 --> 00:06:05.400
the Hindus get credit for, okay? So they did&nbsp;
not have this idea that there's a new number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:05.400 --> 00:06:16.160
which is these two slanted symbols. Nevertheless,&nbsp;
it's really the first use of the term zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:21.880
and the astronomers actually did&nbsp;
employ this notation. However,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:26.640
it was never really equated with nothingness.&nbsp;
We didn't have this idea that there's nothing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:26.640 --> 00:06:32.080
and that nothing is actually represented&nbsp;
by this particular symbol explicitly.

00:06:32.080 --> 00:06:39.360
Now, many histories of mathematics concentrate on&nbsp;
the Mediterranean area and the Asian developments&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:39.360 --> 00:06:45.720
as well. Of course, there were also very&nbsp;
important cultures—in fact, cultures—in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.720 --> 00:06:53.000
Americas: the Mayans, Aztecs, and Incas. And the&nbsp;
Mayan culture is particularly interesting because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:59.520
they had a very interesting arithmetic and quite a&nbsp;
sophisticated calendar reckoning and corresponding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:00.040 --> 00:07:06.000
astronomy. So in Central America, the Mayan&nbsp;
culture—well, it had been around from at least&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:14.520
2000 BC, but there was a classic period from 250&nbsp;
AD to 900 AD when things really developed in a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:14.520 --> 00:07:20.880
rather sophisticated way. And we know that they&nbsp;
had a so-called vigesimal system, which is base&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:28.600
20, and it was actually relatively efficiently&nbsp;
written down with only three symbols—more or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:28.600 --> 00:07:36.360
less a symbol for zero, which was this sort of odd&nbsp;
kind of eye-shaped thing (and in fact, there were&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:36.360 --> 00:07:42.920
quite a lot of variants on the way of writing that&nbsp;
zero), and then there was a dot which represented&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:42.920 --> 00:07:53.040
one, and a horizontal bar which represented&nbsp;
five. So they would count zero, 1, 2, 3, 4,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:53.040 --> 00:08:00.880
5, like this, six like this, up to 19. And then&nbsp;
after 19, well, then they had a base 20 system.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:00.880 --> 00:08:06.560
So these were sort of the basic digits that they&nbsp;
would use, and then they would have these things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:06.560 --> 00:08:13.080
stacked up in a vertical system, not a horizontal&nbsp;
one. And they were very interested in astronomy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:13.080 --> 00:08:21.520
and calendars, and that explains a little bit&nbsp;
that their system for stacking things up was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:21.520 --> 00:08:28.440
not quite what you would expect in a base-20&nbsp;
system. There was an important twist involved.

00:08:28.440 --> 00:08:34.760
So here, for example, is a Maya number. So we&nbsp;
see these symbols stacked one on top of each&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:40.840
other. We recognize this one here as the symbol&nbsp;
for 11—it has two fives and the one. And then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:40.840 --> 00:08:45.400
there's a zero, and then there's a two, and then&nbsp;
there's a three. So what do these various things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:45.400 --> 00:08:54.400
represent? Well, the bottom one was 11, or 11&nbsp;
ones, and here we have 02s, but the next level&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.400 --> 00:09:03.840
does not correspond, as we might imagine, to 20&nbsp;
squared. This next level actually represents how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:03.840 --> 00:09:14.400
many 360s we have, so this would mean that there&nbsp;
are 2 times 360, and the next level represented&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:22.480
20 times 360. So after this, we keep multiplying&nbsp;
by 20, but we have this basic 360. So this means&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.480 --> 00:09:32.200
that we have 3 times 20 times 360s, so I think&nbsp;
that's a total of 22,361. So there's certainly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:39.160
an unevenness to these levels—we have ones, and&nbsp;
then 20s, and then 360s, and then 20 times 360s,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:39.160 --> 00:09:46.360
20 squared times 360s, and so on. And the reason&nbsp;
for that is because they were very interested in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:46.360 --> 00:09:54.120
the calendar—they had a very good understanding&nbsp;
of astronomy and the year especially. So they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:54.120 --> 00:09:59.320
knew there were 365 days in a year, and so 360&nbsp;
was kind of the closest to that. So they had&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:59.920 --> 00:10:07.360
a splitting up of the 360 into 18 periods of 20,&nbsp;
so it was 18 times 20, and then there were five&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:07.360 --> 00:10:12.720
left over. And it was because of that 360&nbsp;
that appeared in their calendar that they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:12.720 --> 00:10:19.960
had a number system that kind of reflected&nbsp;
that aspect of things. So their numbering,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:19.960 --> 00:10:29.320
or their numerology, I think, was very closely&nbsp;
connected somehow with the year, days, and time.

00:10:30.200 --> 00:10:38.320
So as an idea of their accuracy, they knew&nbsp;
that the solar year actually was a little&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:38.320 --> 00:10:49.360
bit more than 365 days, and effectively they&nbsp;
knew that, in our language, it was 365.2420,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:49.360 --> 00:10:58.880
while our current understanding is that it's&nbsp;
365.242198. So this is pretty impressive, kind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:06.040
of accuracy, in their understanding. So the Mayans&nbsp;
did have a symbol for zero, and they used that in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:06.040 --> 00:11:13.960
their positional representation of numbers,&nbsp;
not so much different from the Babylonians.

00:11:13.960 --> 00:11:18.200
Now, what about the ancient Greeks, who&nbsp;
were, of course, sort of the powerhouse&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:18.200 --> 00:11:27.880
of ancient mathematics in terms of developing the&nbsp;
geometry and mathematics that we know today? Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:34.480
their arithmetic was not as impressive as&nbsp;
their geometry. They certainly knew a lot of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:34.480 --> 00:11:41.440
interesting things about arithmetic, but their&nbsp;
actual notational arithmetical tools that they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:41.440 --> 00:11:47.760
had were not always very powerful. In fact,&nbsp;
often they would use the Babylonian system to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:52.680
make calculations. They had a kind of an alphabet&nbsp;
kind of system where they represented numbers by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:52.680 --> 00:11:58.240
letters of the alphabet, but this was cumbersome,&nbsp;
and they did find that the Babylonian system was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:58.240 --> 00:12:07.320
useful to borrow. But we can also see that they&nbsp;
philosophically were not inclined to think about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:07.320 --> 00:12:14.280
zero as a very important concept. Philosophically,&nbsp;
they did not like or were mistrustful of this idea&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:14.280 --> 00:12:22.040
of the void or nothing, and maybe we can attribute&nbsp;
that a little bit to their emphasis on geometry.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:22.040 --> 00:12:28.480
So, for example, if you have a very geometrical&nbsp;
approach to numbers, which they did—they liked&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:28.480 --> 00:12:37.440
to think about numbers as being represented by&nbsp;
physical or geometrical patterns or designs. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:37.440 --> 00:12:43.800
for example, triangular numbers figured&nbsp;
prominently in their thinking: 1, 3, 6, 10,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:43.800 --> 00:12:48.880
and so on. And if you're thinking about something&nbsp;
like triangular numbers represented in this very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:48.880 --> 00:12:57.040
physical way with these little triangular piles&nbsp;
of circles, then it's not very natural for you to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:57.040 --> 00:13:03.560
want to consider zero. Zero doesn't really figure&nbsp;
in this because it's clear that this pattern of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:03.560 --> 00:13:08.560
triangular numbers really ought to start with&nbsp;
one—that's the starting point, and that's the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:08.560 --> 00:13:16.080
next one, and that's the next one. It's somehow&nbsp;
unnatural to talk about zero in this context.

00:13:16.080 --> 00:13:23.520
So aside from their geometrical inclination, they&nbsp;
also had very strong ideas about philosophy. They&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:23.520 --> 00:13:28.440
thought very deeply about what the world was&nbsp;
really about, and they came to this conclusion&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:28.440 --> 00:13:37.080
that it was not really proper to try to&nbsp;
make something out of nothing, right? So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:37.080 --> 00:13:43.200
you know, the idea of nothing or a void was not&nbsp;
sufficiently rich to be able to convert that into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:43.200 --> 00:13:47.760
something. And in some sense, that's what we're&nbsp;
doing, right? When we're thinking about zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:47.760 --> 00:13:52.720
we're thinking about nothing, and then we're&nbsp;
writing a symbol to represent that nothing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:52.720 --> 00:13:59.160
and then that symbol becomes something that&nbsp;
we manipulate along with other numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:59.160 --> 00:14:06.080
So in some way, we're creating something out of&nbsp;
nothing by the use of a modern symbol like this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:06.080 --> 00:14:11.280
but the Greeks did not like that way of&nbsp;
thinking. They thought of both infinity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:11.280 --> 00:14:18.000
and the void as things to be avoided&nbsp;
conceptually—they were problematic.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:26.720
So this philosophical orientation was well&nbsp;
expressed by a prominent Greek philosopher,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:26.720 --> 00:14:35.200
Parmenides, who was a big influence on&nbsp;
Plato, and he wrote on this topic in a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:35.200 --> 00:14:39.600
number of different places. So here are some&nbsp;
quotes from Parmenides. He says that "it is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:39.600 --> 00:14:49.200
necessary to speak and to think about what&nbsp;
is, for being is, but nothing is not." Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:49.200 --> 00:14:54.680
this is in the direction of "we should&nbsp;
talk about things which actually are;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:54.680 --> 00:14:59.040
we can't talk about things which&nbsp;
are not, because they're not."&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:00.080 --> 00:15:07.280
Another quote: "Nothing comes from nothing"—this&nbsp;
idea that you can't take nothing, that concept&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:15.200
nothing, and create something out of it. That's a&nbsp;
vacuous kind of activity; you shouldn't do that.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:15.200 --> 00:15:23.640
So we also read from him that "for this view that&nbsp;
that which is not exists can never predominate."&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:23.640 --> 00:15:30.560
He's saying that the idea that we can consider&nbsp;
that which is not—so that which is not—and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:30.560 --> 00:15:39.080
actually objectify that and create something&nbsp;
out of it, that's not a valid way of thinking.

00:15:39.080 --> 00:15:44.080
So Parmenides had a big influence on Plato, who&nbsp;
actually named one of his dialogues after him, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:44.080 --> 00:15:48.600
this really, you know, was representative of the&nbsp;
Greek way of thinking and explains to some extent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:48.600 --> 00:15:58.920
why theirs was not a fertile arithmetic for this&nbsp;
idea of a symbol for zero to develop and blossom.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:59.880 --> 00:16:03.840
I'd like to mention also that the Hebrew&nbsp;
tradition is also in this direction. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:03.840 --> 00:16:08.800
in the Hebrew tradition, the void&nbsp;
is also treated with suspicion,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:08.800 --> 00:16:13.320
and one tries to avoid it. So the void&nbsp;
is considered to be a state of separation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:13.320 --> 00:16:19.800
from God. So first there was the void, and&nbsp;
then there was God creating other stuff,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:19.800 --> 00:16:28.040
and so the void is some kind of thing that&nbsp;
we want to stay away from—it's not pleasant.

00:16:28.040 --> 00:16:34.840
So there's a philosophical orientation&nbsp;
that is very close to people's thinking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:34.840 --> 00:16:40.040
about this subject. You know, what&nbsp;
does it mean to contemplate nothing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:40.040 --> 00:16:45.040
for example? What would the world be like if&nbsp;
there was nothing? It's a very profound question,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:45.040 --> 00:16:47.960
and people have been thinking about&nbsp;
these kinds of things for a long time,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:47.960 --> 00:16:54.360
and one's orientation towards this kind&nbsp;
of philosophical position would naturally&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:54.360 --> 00:17:00.960
influence one's mathematics and the kind&nbsp;
of mathematics that one might want to do.

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:07.400
And so now we come to the heroes of this&nbsp;
story—the culture that really introduced&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:07.400 --> 00:17:12.800
zero the way we know it now. And now we&nbsp;
recognize that this was a fundamentally,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:12.800 --> 00:17:18.040
crucially important development in the history&nbsp;
of science, and I have talked about that in a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:18.040 --> 00:17:25.160
previous video on the Hindu-Arabic numbers. So&nbsp;
we're talking about ancient Indian philosophy,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:25.160 --> 00:17:30.720
religion, and mathematics. The Indus Valley&nbsp;
culture goes back to around 3,000 BC,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:30.720 --> 00:17:38.000
but we have evidence to suggest that they were&nbsp;
thinking along somewhat modern lines around 350&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:38.000 --> 00:17:46.320
BC, where the Brahmi notation for numerals was&nbsp;
starting to look pretty similar to the modern&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:46.320 --> 00:17:53.840
system. And they had a positional base 10 system&nbsp;
that was in place around 500 AD. So here are some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:53.840 --> 00:18:02.480
original kind of numerals—you can sort of see some&nbsp;
similarities with some of our current numbers.

00:18:02.480 --> 00:18:07.040
Now, what's interesting in the Indian&nbsp;
point of view here, amongst other things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:07.040 --> 00:18:15.600
is that their philosophical orientation seemed&nbsp;
to predispose them to being happy with the idea&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:15.600 --> 00:18:22.000
of thinking about nothing as a legitimate&nbsp;
object for study and incorporating it into&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:29.080
mathematics. The Indians were not afraid of&nbsp;
nothing, philosophically. In fact, they had a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:29.080 --> 00:18:33.000
kind of reverence for it—they were very&nbsp;
comfortable with the idea of nothingness and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:40.440
emptiness. Maybe simplistically we could say that&nbsp;
nothing was viewed as a state from which we arise,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:40.440 --> 00:18:44.400
and it's a state that we eventually return&nbsp;
to. So maybe from an Indian point of view,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:44.400 --> 00:18:50.880
there's nothing to be afraid of—it's a&nbsp;
sort of natural part of the whole story.

00:18:50.880 --> 00:18:55.680
In any case, in Sanskrit, they had lots&nbsp;
of different words representing different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:55.680 --> 00:19:02.840
aspects of emptiness, void, nothing,&nbsp;
and so on. So they conceptually had a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:02.840 --> 00:19:09.640
framework in which nothing naturally played a&nbsp;
reasonable role, and this was then, of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:09.640 --> 00:19:16.240
very crucial in this development after they&nbsp;
had these numbers, to eventually introduce&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:16.240 --> 00:19:24.920
actually a symbol for zero that turned out to&nbsp;
be another number, essentially on par with the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:24.920 --> 00:19:35.480
ones that they already had. So we have evidence&nbsp;
that a dot for zero was in place around 200 BC,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:35.480 --> 00:19:44.000
and that gradually was then replaced with the more&nbsp;
familiar round circle zero. And by around 500 AD,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:51.280
it was in place as a placeholder in a decimal&nbsp;
system pretty much the same as we have today.

00:19:51.280 --> 00:19:57.160
And then we come to Brahmagupta, a prominent&nbsp;
Indian mathematician and astronomer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:57.160 --> 00:20:04.720
who around 628 AD took an important additional&nbsp;
step to establish zero not just as a placeholder&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:04.720 --> 00:20:12.360
in a notational system for more general numbers,&nbsp;
but actually to recognize that zero was an entity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:12.360 --> 00:20:22.040
that had an independence—it had a role to play.&nbsp;
And that role, in fact, turned out to be a rather&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:22.040 --> 00:20:28.880
important one in arithmetic. So that zero could&nbsp;
be the result of an arithmetical computation: so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:28.880 --> 00:20:35.040
5 - 5 equals 0. That is then an equation that you&nbsp;
could actually write down, whereas formerly it was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:45.080
difficult to say that 3 + 0 = 3. You can multiply&nbsp;
by 0: 0 times 7 = 0. You can subtract 0 from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:45.080 --> 00:20:53.400
something: 4 - 0 is 4. In fact, he even discusses&nbsp;
division by zero and had an understanding that if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:53.400 --> 00:20:58.600
you take a number and you divide by zero,&nbsp;
you're getting something like infinite.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:00.480 --> 00:21:02.560
All right, so this is a very huge step.

00:21:02.560 --> 00:21:08.040
And I've talked about, you know, the importance&nbsp;
of the Hindu-Arabic system in many places,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:08.040 --> 00:21:14.200
and it's really not possible to overestimate&nbsp;
the importance of this whole development in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:14.200 --> 00:21:17.640
the modern world. The world that we&nbsp;
live in, the highly technological,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:17.640 --> 00:21:23.280
mathematical world, rests very&nbsp;
solidly on this—well, to us,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:23.280 --> 00:21:28.920
it seems relatively simple and straightforward&nbsp;
because we've been taught from a very early age,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:28.920 --> 00:21:34.560
over and over and over again, how this numerical&nbsp;
system works. But it's actually full of subtlety&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:34.560 --> 00:21:42.320
and richness, this Hindu-Arabic system, and the&nbsp;
zero, of course, plays a very important role.

00:21:42.320 --> 00:21:49.840
Now, if we move ahead to European times, to&nbsp;
more modern times, the role of nothing or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:49.840 --> 00:21:55.920
zero was still actually quite contentious&nbsp;
in the 16th, 17th, and 18th centuries,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:55.920 --> 00:22:02.400
where people were examining the physical universe&nbsp;
much more carefully. And, for example, questions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:02.400 --> 00:22:09.240
about whether it was possible to consider empty&nbsp;
space or not were being discussed. So the ancient&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:09.240 --> 00:22:16.440
Greeks had reservations about being able to treat&nbsp;
empty space as something sort of independent of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:16.440 --> 00:22:23.080
other stuff. But 17th and 18th-century scientists&nbsp;
started investigating the possibility of thinking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:23.080 --> 00:22:30.360
about space as being free from any stuff inside&nbsp;
it—trying to create a vacuum, for example. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:30.360 --> 00:22:35.360
in the framework of Newton's laws, I mean,&nbsp;
these are sort of operating in sort of empty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:35.360 --> 00:22:42.720
space quite happily. But if we fast forward then&nbsp;
again to 20th-century physics, things become then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:42.720 --> 00:22:50.760
again more complicated, and the confidence and the&nbsp;
certainty that maybe 19th-century mathematicians&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:50.760 --> 00:22:56.280
had about the void or vacuum started going in&nbsp;
the other direction again, and people started&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:56.280 --> 00:23:03.760
becoming more aware that this was still a rather&nbsp;
problematic concept and actually full of subtlety.

00:23:03.760 --> 00:23:11.120
So in modern 20th-century physics, the&nbsp;
vacuum is treated as a really central but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:11.120 --> 00:23:19.200
very complicated and rich kind of concept. So&nbsp;
to the modern physicist, the vacuum is full of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:19.200 --> 00:23:27.840
possibilities—it's not at all just empty space&nbsp;
and nothing in it. So this is largely due to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:27.840 --> 00:23:34.000
the role of quantum mechanics and a certain&nbsp;
principle called the uncertainty principle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:39.040
which roughly tells us that we can't really&nbsp;
know everything about a situation, let's say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:39.040 --> 00:23:43.680
right? And that goes for any kind of&nbsp;
situation, even a situation where it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:43.680 --> 00:23:48.200
looks like there might be nothing in it. So&nbsp;
if you have a situation where you have some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:48.200 --> 00:23:55.840
empty piece of space and there's nothing in it,&nbsp;
you still can't know everything about it. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:55.840 --> 00:24:02.120
that can be interpreted as saying that there's a&nbsp;
lowest possible energy sort of for empty space,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:02.120 --> 00:24:09.600
but you can't really make that energy completely&nbsp;
zero—there's always some energy there. That's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:09.600 --> 00:24:17.800
a kind of a bottom possible energy, but that&nbsp;
supports various strange things that might happen.

00:24:17.800 --> 00:24:25.800
So in the modern vacuum, physicists think that&nbsp;
there are all these simultaneous creations and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:25.800 --> 00:24:32.040
annihilations of particle and antiparticle&nbsp;
pairs that are sort of instantaneously&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:32.040 --> 00:24:36.360
happening where we, you know, have a little&nbsp;
bit of empty space and suddenly there's an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:36.360 --> 00:24:42.960
electron and a positron. So an electron has&nbsp;
an antiparticle called a positron, and these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:42.960 --> 00:24:48.000
things can be created sort of out of nothing,&nbsp;
more or less, and then shortly thereafter,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:54.240
they can then annihilate each other and go back&nbsp;
to nothing. So this quantum vacuum is sort of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:54.240 --> 00:24:59.680
seething with all these possibilities of these&nbsp;
particles emerging for a short period of time,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:59.680 --> 00:25:08.280
and so on. So it's a very rich and mysterious&nbsp;
kind of concept. So the modern physicist now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:08.280 --> 00:25:18.280
is returning to not being so sure what nothing&nbsp;
means, actually, in the kind of physical world.

00:25:18.280 --> 00:25:25.040
And so this is a very interesting story about&nbsp;
nothing, and I think the last word has not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:25.040 --> 00:25:34.800
been said. And I would like to really emphasize&nbsp;
the possibility that maybe even in mathematics,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:34.800 --> 00:25:44.160
which is at least potentially independent of these&nbsp;
quantum mysteries, even in mathematics there's the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:44.160 --> 00:25:51.680
potential room for thinking about nothing or the&nbsp;
void in a different or an additional way to what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:51.680 --> 00:25:56.640
we already have. So I don't necessarily want&nbsp;
to change the role of zero, which is a great,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:56.640 --> 00:26:02.000
you know, very important concept in our&nbsp;
number system and so on, but I do want us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:11.120
to think more liberally about the possible role&nbsp;
of nothing—a more fundamental kind of nothing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:11.120 --> 00:26:17.720
than actually zero. So zero is still something&nbsp;
that's been created out of nothing, but I want&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:17.720 --> 00:26:25.560
to propose that there's room in mathematics&nbsp;
for nothing, which is still just nothing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:25.560 --> 00:26:31.360
okay? It hasn't been converted into something.&nbsp;
We don't have to create something from nothing;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:31.360 --> 00:26:39.320
we can think about nothing itself, and&nbsp;
that can be a concept that can help us.

00:26:39.320 --> 00:26:45.920
And so, okay, that's what I want to do—I want&nbsp;
to introduce nothing into mathematics again,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:45.920 --> 00:26:56.920
but in a more primitive, fundamental, really void&nbsp;
kind of fashion. I think there's a role to play,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:56.920 --> 00:27:01.040
and that is especially clear when we have&nbsp;
this multiset point of view that we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:01.040 --> 00:27:08.280
getting used to here. So in our next video,&nbsp;
I want to talk about nothing in a multiset&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:08.280 --> 00:27:15.040
context and why mathematics really does&nbsp;
need new thinking about nothing. I hope&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:15.040 --> 00:27:28.160
you'll join me for that. I'm Norman&nbsp;
Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

00:27:28.160 --> 00:27:28.677
[Music]

